# Worktrunk

`wt` wraps raw @git/worktree so you address a branch by *name*, not by path —
`wt switch feature` creates or jumps to the worktree for `feature`, computing the
directory from a path template (default `.worktrees/<branch>`). Built to run many
agents/branches in parallel without the manual `git worktree add` + `cd` dance.

Where @git/worktree is the plumbing (you pick the path, you prune), `wt` is the
porcelain: path templates, an interactive picker, lifecycle @wt/hook automation,
LLM commit messages, and a one-shot @wt/merge that squashes → rebases → lands →
removes. Config lives in @wt/config.

## Install

```bash
# macOS / Linux
brew install worktrunk && wt config shell install

# any platform with Rust
cargo install worktrunk && wt config shell install
```

Also: winget (`git-wt` on Windows), pacman (Arch), conda/pixi. `wt config shell
install` wires the shell function that lets `wt switch` actually change your
directory — without it `wt` can't `cd` the parent shell.

## Branch addressing

Every command that takes a branch accepts these shortcuts:

| Token | Means |
|-------|-------|
| `^` | the default branch (main/master) |
| `@` | the current branch / worktree |
| `-` | the previous worktree (toggle back) |
| `pr:N` | GitHub PR #N's branch |
| `mr:N` | GitLab MR !N's branch |
| a full PR/MR URL | the same |

## Subcommands

| Command | jd | Does |
|---------|-----|------|
| `switch` | @wt/switch | create / jump to a worktree, picker, PR checkout |
| `list` | @wt/list | table of all worktrees + status |
| `merge` | @wt/merge | squash, rebase, land, remove — one shot |
| `remove` | @wt/remove | delete a worktree (and usually its branch) |
| `step` | @wt/step | granular building blocks (commit, rebase, diff…) |

`switch`, `merge`, and `remove` are the high-level verbs; `step` exposes their
individual phases for scripting.
